Labor mobility



1. Background


A major economic objective of public goods, provided by a government, is the job creation (= attracting firms) that would provide income to its citizen. When this does not work, or works less than somewhere else, regional income disparity arises.


1.1 Labor mobility is the movement of labor across industries or regions


1.2 Many factors affect labor mobility

  • incomes, wages
  • distances
    • physical
    • cultural
    • psychological
    • regulatory
  • non-economic causes
    • wars
    • armed conflicts
    • natural disasters etc.


1.3 Some often asked questions

  • labor mobility and growth
  • labor mobility and regional disparity
  • labor mobility and knowledge spillover
